To confirm that the Elastic Agent is functioning correctly and forwarding logs to your Elastic SIEM, weâ€™ll generate some security-related events using Nmap.

Nmap (Network Mapper) is a powerful open-source tool for network exploration and security auditing. It can:

Scan hosts for open ports
Identify services running on target systems
Detect operating systems and network vulnerabilities

ğŸ›  1. Install Nmap (if not using Kali Linux)
If youâ€™re not using Kali Linux (where Nmap is preinstalled), install it by running:

sudo apt update
sudo apt-get install nmap

ğŸŒ 2. Identify Your Kali VMâ€™s IP Address
To scan your Kali VM or host machine, youâ€™ll need the correct IP address. Run:

ip a
Look for an entry like inet 192.168.x.x under the correct network interface (e.g., eth0, wlan0).

ğŸ” 3. Run Basic Nmap Scan
Run a basic scan on your Kali VMâ€™s IP address:

sudo nmap
Replace with your actual IP address.

ğŸ’¡ Example:

sudo nmap 192.168.1.10

ğŸŒŸ 4. Run Additional Nmap Scans for More Events
Generate more security events by running different types of scans:

TCP SYN Scan (Stealth Scan):

sudo nmap -sS
(Common for identifying open ports stealthily.)

TCP Connect Scan:

sudo nmap -sT
(Used when SYN scan is not available.)

Full Port Scan:

sudo nmap -p-
(Scans all 65,535 ports.)

Service Version Detection:

sudo nmap -sV
(Identifies services and versions running on open ports.)

OS Detection and Traceroute:

sudo nmap -A
(Performs OS detection, version detection, script scanning, and traceroute.)

Verify Security Events in Elastic SIEM
Head back to your Elastic SIEM dashboard.
Go to Kibana â†’ SIEM â†’ Detections and check for logs related to Nmap scans, such as:
Open port detections
Suspicious network scanning activity
Service enumeration events
